<dl id="n08057n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08057n">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08057n"> 57(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Xpi Chrismon <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08057n"><li>FW 119.17 </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/lexe.htm#n08057n">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/l39e.htm#n08057n">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08057n">MS BL 47473-36v</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:332 <a name="ed3" href="../../ff/fdra/eda.htm#ed3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/ed3.htm#n08057n">Draft: I.5&sect;1.3</a>/4.3</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Plate XI., fol. 124 R., exhibits the commencement of verse 38 of the 27th chapter of St. Matthew, &ldquo;Tunc crucifixerant XPI cum eo duos latrones&rdquo; &hellip; The &ldquo;XPI,&rdquo; which seems to belong to the sentence, is, as pointed out by Sir John Gilbert, probably only the medi&aelig;val note-mark composed of the monogram of &ldquo;Christi,&rdquo; which was arbitrarily used to call attention to remarkable passages. It was known as the Chrismon.&rdquo; <small> Sir Edward Sullivan, <a name="BOK1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BOK1"><cite title="source">The Book of Kells</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1920) 13/18</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Entered via an extra-draft note on BL-471b-67v (<cite>JJA</cite> 46:340) </mm> </dd></dl>
